Class PostalAddress

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.nyu.cs.addressbook.component.PostalAddress
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Cloneable, Comparable<PostalAddress>

    public final class PostalAddress
extends Object
implements Cloneable, Comparable<PostalAddress>
    Author:
    shenli

    The PostalAddress class represents postal address information.

    PostalAddress are constant; their value could not be changed after they are created. Because PostalAddress objects are immutable they could be shared.

      • equals

        public boolean equals(Object o)
        Compares the specified object with this PostalAddress for equality. Returns true if and only if the specified object is also a PostalAddress object, both objects have the same zipcode, state, city, and street.

        This implementation first checks if the specified object is this PostalAddress. If so, it returns true; if not, it checks if the specified object is a PostalAddress object. If not, it returns false; if so, it iterates over both PostalAddress objects, comparing corresponding fields. If any comparison returns false, this method returns false. Otherwise it returns true when the iterations complete.

      • toString

        public String toString()
        Returns string representation of this postal address. The string format is as "street\ncity, state XXXXX\n The United States", where XXXXX is the zipcode. (Each of the capital letters represents a single decimal digit.)

        If the zipcode is too small to fill up its field, the field is padded with leading zeros. For example, if the value of the zipcode is 1234, the zipcode string representation will be "01234".

        Overrides:
        toString in class Object
        Returns:
        a string comprising postal address fields

      • clone

        public PostalAddress clone()
        Creates and returns a copy of this object.

        The method clone for class PostalAddress performs a specific cloning operation. First, if the class of this PostalAddress object does not implement the interface Cloneable, then a CloneNotSupportedException is thrown. Note that all arrays are considered to implement the interface Cloneable. Otherwise, this method creates a new instance of the class of this PostalAddress object and initializes all its fields with exactly the contents of the corresponding fields of this object, as if by assignment; the contents of the fields are not themselves cloned. Thus, this method performs a "shallow copy" of this object, not a "deep copy" operation.

        Overrides:
        clone in class Object
        Returns:
        a clone of this instance
        Throws:

        public int compareTo(PostalAddress pa)
        Compares the postal addresses represented by two PostalAddress objects. Returns a negative integer, zero, or a positive integer as this object is less than, equal to, or greater than the specified object.
